shell is allowing us to communicate with the operating system
bash (bourn again shell) is the most popular shell
echo $SHELL to get current shell used
chsh -s <shellpath> <username> to change a shell of a user
bash allow us to use tab completion and expansion 
* => all 
{1..100} from 1 to 100
{1,3,7} 1 , 3 , 7 
alias t="tar -cvzf"
to autoload this alias add it to your {.bashrc,.profile} => both file autoload when you open new shell
env => to print all env variables
x=y to set env variable
export x=y to set env variable and make it readable to all children proccess
to autoload it to each shell => add to .bashrc or .profile
echo $PATH to print the path env varialbe ( has all binaries directories )
which <command> to display the command full path
whatis <command> to display the usage of a command
PS1 => env var that display the prompot for your ( echo $PS1 )

/etc/passwd  users info
getent passwd to display the /etc/passwd ( cat /etc/passwd )
/etc/shadow  users encrypted passwords
/etc/group  groups info
getent group to display the /etc/group ( cat /etc/group )
User Account vs System Account vs Superuser Account
can login       can't login       root 

useradd <username> add new user to the server
groupadd <groupname> add new group to the server
groupadd -g <groupname> to set the group id while creating it
passwd <username> update password for a user
usermod <options> <username> to udpate a user
-s <shellpath> to set the user login shell
-u <user id> to set the user id
-g <groupname> to set the main group of the user
-aG <groupname> to add a new group to the user
id <username> to display info about a user
userdel <username>  to delete a user
groupdel <groupname> to delete a group
/etc/sudoers have users and groups sudo permissions
visudo to edit /etc/sudoers
sudo -l to display your sudo permissions




command --help  => to see how to use a commmand
man command     => to open maual page of the command

\u  username
\h  short hostname
\H  full hostname
\w  current directory
\W  basename of cwd
\d  date
\t  time (24h HH:MM:SS)
\T  time (12h)
\@  time (am/pm)
\A  time (24h HH:MM)
\$  # if root, $ otherwise
\#  command number
\!  history number
\n  new line
\e  escape character
\[  start non-printing
\]  end non-printing

